data.name: Label1.Text
data.value: This project has been revisited on 3rd June 2021 and the following improvements have been made: 1) All control colours (text and backgrounds) now use system colours which automatically adjust when high contrast themes are in use 2) If you're using Windows 10 and have increased the size of text and other items on screen (also known as high DPI), you may have noticed that the forms are blurry. This project is now DPI aware which means the forms are no longer blurry 3) Dialogue boxes now have icons and titles to better communicate alerts and other information 4) A new icon

data.name: lb_text_intro.Text
data.value: Welcome to the Petrol Station Simulator, helping you to simulate the process of using a petrol pump. Using the program is simple but if you need help, you're in the right place. Use the tabs above to find out how to use this program. I hope it has helped you.

data.name: lb_text_price.Text
data.value: The first thing to do is to enter a price for 1 litre of fuel. This is because this number will be used as part of a calculation for the amount of money to pay for a transaction. If the input is innapropriate, you'll receive an error message, telling you to enter a price (in pounds and pence). To enter the price, select the text box (next to the label, "Price per Litre" and type it. To find out more about dispensing the fuel, please refer to section three, "Dispensing the Fuel".

data.name: lb_text_dispensing.Text
data.value: After you've entered a price per litre, click "Dispense" to start the refuelling process. As you refuel, you will see that the amount of fuel dispensed increases by 0.01 litres. The amount of money to pay for the current transaction will be calculated using the following formula: Amount to pay (rounded to 2 decimal places) = fuel dispensed X price per litre. When you want to stop refuelling, click "Stop". This will immediately stop the process and you will see the amount of fuel dispensed (in litres) and the amount to pay (in pounds and pence). To learn more about adding the current transaction to the totals, please refer to section four, "Adding Transactions to Totals". When the process is occuring, the current status will be "In Use". Otherwise, it will be "NOT In Use".

data.name: lb_text_adding_to_totals.Text
data.value: When you have finished a transaction, you can add it to the totals by clicking "Add to Totals". When you click this button, the current amount of fuel dispensed will be added to the total fuel (still in litres) and the amount paid will be added to the total money made (still in pounds and pence). The values for the current transaction will be cleared, allowing you to start a new one.

data.name: lb_text_no_fuel.Text
data.value: The amount of fuel that the petrol pump can provide is limited to 100 litres. As transactions occur, this value will decrease. You can see how much fuel is left by looking at the green bar (found on the bottom left of the program). The green part of this feature shows how much fuel there is against the amount before the first transaction. Also, there is a number above it to show exactly how much fuel is left. When this number reaches zero, the petrol pump will stop refuelling automatically and you'll have to add the last transaction to the totals. Once this is done, the status will be "CLOSED" and resetting the simulator is required. To find out how to reset the simulator, please refer to section six, "Resetting the Simulator".

data.name: lb_text_reset.Text
data.value: If you need to reset the simulator, click Reset to instantly set all values to what they were when you opened the program. You'll need to do this if the petrol pump is closed or you simply want to start again.
